-! # how to errors: 021-no-name-imu.zo
-!
-! @cmd: `zo build 021-no-name-imu.zo`
-!
-! Every piece of data in your workstation needs a handle. 
-! In zo, we don't allow "Ghost Variables"—values that exist 
-! but have no name. 
-!
-! If you provide a type and a value, but forget the identifier (the name), 
-! the compiler stops you. You cannot grasp what you cannot name.

fun main() {
  -- Mistake: Missing the name between `imu` and `: int`.
  imu : int = 42;

  -- Mistake: Missing the name between `imu` and `:= 42`.
  imu := 42;
}

-! ## the diagnostic:
-!
-! The compiler identifies the `imu` keyword and scans for a name. 
-! Because it finds a colon `:` instead of an identifier, it triggers 

-! ## try this.
-!
-! 1. Give the variable a name, like `imu age: int = 42;`. 
-!    Now you have a handle to use this data later in your program.
-! 2. Try removing the `: int` part entirely: `imu = 42;`. 
-!    Notice how the error remains the same—Zo always needs a name, even if it
-!    can figure out the type for you.
-! 3. Try this with `mut`. Does `mut : int = 10;` produce the same total
-!    information map?

-- EXPECTED OUTPUT:
-- [E0021] Error: Expected identifier after `imu`
--    ┌─ 021-no-name-imu.zo:13:7
--    │
-- 13 │   imu : int = 42;
--    │       ^ expected a name here
--    │
--    = Note: An immutable local declaration requires a name so you can refer to it.
--    = Help: Insert a name at line 13, column 7. Example: `imu my_value: int = 42;`
-- ────╯

-- this is the design based `hint`, `title`, `note`, `help` as to be implement in error message.